contents.name: Figure ResCS.02 - Software Resource Specification Relationship
contents.publish:qualifiedname: SID Models::Resource Domain::Resource ABE::_Resource Addendum Figuers::Computing and Software Addendum Figures::Figure ResCS.02 - Software Resource Specification Relationship

publish:property.name: Description
publish:property.publish:value: There can be many types of relationships that exist among SoftwareResourceSpecifications. These are shown in the Figure below....

publish:property.name: Name
publish:property.publish:value: Figure ResCS.02 - Software Resource Specification Relationship

ownedComment.body: There can be many types of relationships that exist among SoftwareResourceSpecifications. These are shown in the Figure below. The SoftwareResourceSpecRelationship entity has purposely been made non-abstract so that new types of simple relationships can be defined in addition to those shown. If base set of attributes in it are not sufficient then new subclasses can be explicitly modelled or the Characteristic pattern can be used to dynamically add the attributes to a new type. The SoftwareSpecRefinementRelationship subclass defines divisions of a SoftwareResourceSpecification into two or more other specifications. Or fusions of two or more specifications into a single specification. Or one specification can be substituted for another. The SoftwareSpecConstraintRelationship subclass allows additional constraints to be defined for involved specification. The SymmetricConstraint attribute of this subclass is used indicate if the relationship is from the perspective of just one specification or from both for example, A constrains B, and B constrains A. The SoftwareSpecAlternativeRelationship subclass defines specifications that are alternates of others. Its attributes indicate if the alternate is an exact alternate. The symmetric attribute indicates whether A is an alternate for B and B is an alternate for A, or A is an alternate for B only.

contents.name: Figure ResCS.08 - Model Association Enhancements - 1
contents.publish:qualifiedname: SID Models::Resource Domain::Resource ABE::_Resource Addendum Figuers::Computing and Software Addendum Figures::Figure ResCS.08 - Model Association Enhancements - 1

publish:property.name: Description
publish:property.publish:value: As mentioned earlier, a number of associations have been enhanced and added to support the requirements of today’s digital world. This section describes them....

publish:property.name: Name
publish:property.publish:value: Figure ResCS.08 - Model Association Enhancements - 1

ownedComment.body: As mentioned earlier, a number of associations have been enhanced and added to support the requirements of today’s digital world. This section describes them. The Figure below shows one group of associations that were added/enhanced. The association between ResourceElement and InstalledSoftware deserves a few comments. First, the association may appear to be redundant, because a CompoundResource is composed of Logical, Physical, and Compound Resources. However, since ResourceElements can be realized purely by Software, this fact was deemed important enough to justify adding a direct association between the two entities. Second, Figure CS.04 – Software Specification and Resource Specification shows a similar association between CompoundResourceSpecification and SoftwareSpecification. The reason for the difference is that there is no ResourceElementSpecification entity. The InstalledSoftwareRuns (InstalledSoftware) association has been added to support scenarios such as an operating system running desktop software or a virtual machine operating system running a java virtual machine operating system. The addition of the association between Supplier and ResourceSpecification was mentioned in a previous section of this document. It is shown here. The addition of the ResourceReferences association class was added to parallel the recursive association between ResourceSpecifications. It enables one Resource to reference another for a variety of reasons, such as one Resource replacing or being an alternate of another or to model a hierarchy of Resources.

ownedComment.body: A RunningSoftwareStatistic entity has also been introduced as shown in the Figure below. RunningSoftwareStatistic represents the characteristics of the running software, such as memory, physical disk, and CPU used. The characteristics are represented by the generalized attribute resourceUse with the type of use represented by the instance of Resource used. The useDateTime attribute records when the Resource is being or has been used.

contents.name: Figure ResCS.04 - Software Specification and Resource Specification
contents.publish:qualifiedname: SID Models::Resource Domain::Resource ABE::_Resource Addendum Figuers::Computing and Software Addendum Figures::Figure ResCS.04 - Software Specification and Resource Specification

publish:property.name: Description
publish:property.publish:value: The Figure below shows associations between SoftwareSpecification, CompoundResourceSpec, and ResourceSpecification....

publish:property.name: Name
publish:property.publish:value: Figure ResCS.04 - Software Specification and Resource Specification

ownedComment.body: The Figure below shows associations between SoftwareSpecification, CompoundResourceSpec, and ResourceSpecification. The first simple association is used to specify that a CompoundResourceSpecification may be realized by SoftwareSpecification alone and not a combination of at least one PhysicalResourceSpec and at least one LogicalResourceSpec. This changes the definition of a CompoundResourceSpec and a CompoundResource that will be shown in an upcoming figure. The association class is used to show the status of a SoftwareSpecification that can run on any ResourceSpecification. For example, the status may reflect that it can or can no longer be run. The association was made so that any type of resource (within reason!) could run Software, such as a CompoundResource, LogicalDevice or PhysicalDevice. The SoftwareSpecificationUses association was added so that any type of Software could use any type of Resource (again, within reason). For example, Software could use memory (logical or physical), memory databases, or physical disks of any type. HostingPlatformRequirementSpec has been introduced to represent the requirements that must be fulfilled by the platform on which the InstalledSoftware will run (e.g. compute, storage, network). The derived association “/SoftwareSpecificatonRequires” is used to document the requirements necessary to a platform to be capable of hosting the concerned software before it is installed.

contents.name: Figure ResCS.01 - Software Resource Specification

publish:property.name: Description
publish:property.publish:value: The following Figure shows the details of the corresponding Software Specification classes....

publish:property.name: Name
publish:property.publish:value: Figure ResCS.01 - Software Resource Specification

ownedComment.body: The following Figure shows the details of the corresponding Software Specification classes. SoftwareResourceSpecification in the figure depicts the attributes that are shared by every instance of an associated SoftwareResource entity. The SoftwareSpecification entity has been shown separately from the APISpecification entity because it contains attributes unique to it as shown in the figure. For an example of APISpecification entity usage please refer to Root Guidebook. The composite/atomic pattern has been applied to the SoftwareSpecification entity to allow for groupings of Software, such as the software module specifications that are contained within an application specification. Note that the application specification is not shown as a subclass of SoftwareSpecification. This is because there have been no unique attributes discovered for it. <Note>Note that there are many attributes and associations inherited by SoftwareResourceSpecification, such as the association to SupplierPartner from ResourceSpecification as well as others from LogicalResourceSpecification (Refer to the corresponding section).</Note>
